<span style="color: rgb(194, 165, 97); font-family: Courier;">'''Dullness''' is an endless labyrinth composed of rooms that vary randomly in size and shape, with varying shapes merged into each space's structure. Some rooms may resemble the dimensions of a small bedroom, while others can exceed the size of a large stadium. The layout of this level is inconsistent and unpredictable, as rooms may suddenly cut off into different areas . Furthermore, the geometry of the level shifts, making navigation nearly impossible. All rooms of the level are empty and features a dull monotonous yellow. The surfaces throughout are entirely smooth and have proven to be indestructible. It is thought that every area within '''Dullness''' is distinct, as no two spaces share the same layout or structure.</span>

<span style="color: rgb(194, 165, 97); font-family: Courier;">The level is completely silent, with no sounds can be made within it. As a result, wanderers will slowly descend into madness while navigating the corridors. Regrettably, consuming [[Object 1|Almond Water]] does not mitigate the onset of insanity. Furthermore, a dense fog envelops the level, hindering visibility. Although light sources can penetrate this haze, they will flicker out within a few minutes, as all lighting devices brought into the level will eventually fail. It is important to highlight that all communication lines will be severed upon entry, making any attempts to seek help futile. Additionally, the level has an isolating characteristic that prevents two living beings from encountering one another, intensifying the feeling of loneliness. Nevertheless, there have been occasional reports of human presence within the level, including scattered notes and discarded Almond Water bottles.</span>

<span style="color: rgb(194, 165, 97); font-family: Courier;">A soft breeze of unknown origin flows through the entire level, frequently causing temperature changes in Dullness. It has been observed that larger, open spaces tend to be cooler than confined ones, as there is more room for air to move. This breeze shifts direction unpredictably, and the reasons behind this phenomenon remain unclear. Furthermore, fluorescent light panels may be attached to the ceiling, serving as the sole source of illumination in the level. The operation of these lights is a mystery, as they appear seamlessly integrated into the surface without any visible wiring or connections. Notably, these panels operate silently. Many explorers have reported experiencing headaches and sudden memory flashbacks after looking at the lights for a brief time.</span>

<div style="text-align: center; margin-top: 3em">
<div style="background: rgba(61, 44, 23, 0.55); padding: 0.5rem 1rem 0.10rem; border: 2px solid rgb(194, 165, 97); border-radius: 5px; box-shadow: 0px 10px 30px rgb(125, 94, 47); margin: 2.5em 40px; text-align: center;">
<span class="titlebox" style="color: #ffffff; background: rgb(61, 44, 23); color: rgb(194, 165, 97); border-left: 3px solid rgb(194, 165, 97); border-right: 3px solid rgb(194, 165, 97); border-radius: 10px; background: rgba(48, 42, 27); font-family: Courier; ">'''Addendum''' — Recovered Audio Log</span>
<div style="text-align: center; font-size: 27px; color: rgb(194, 165, 97); font-family: Courier">'''''Wanderings'''''</div>


<span style="font-family: Courier; color: rgb(194, 165, 97);">My name is Ryan Greenfield, and I think I may have found a new level.</span>

<span style="font-family: Courier; color: rgb(194, 165, 97);">It began when I was back in Level 0. I was wanderin' around, y'know? Lookin' for an exit like a sensible person. But, after about, let's see, a few hours after walking, the entire level shook. Like an earthquake! I stumbled about, tryna find a wall to stabilize myself on, but suddenly, the floor below me collapsed, and I fell through the Void. I fell for quite some time, before I suddenly blacked out for... God knows how long before I ended up here. The walls... there were a solid dull yellow, and they were perfectly smooth, too! I explored the maze, and my travels resulted in me seeing the term "space" being bent to its greatest limits.</span>

<span style="font-family: Courier; color: rgb(194, 165, 97);">I've seen spaces smaller than a pencil's width. Small crevices in the walls, if you will. I've seen spaces larger than skyscrapers in height and greater than stadiums in width. It felt so weird. I could be walking through a bedroom-sized area before walking into a narrow hallway with a height that extended up beyond my own vision! But, y'know, I felt my head getting a bit wonky and funky, so I did the age-old technique of noclipping and hoping for the best.</span>

<span style="font-family: Courier; color: rgb(194, 165, 97);">It didn't work.</span>

<span style="font-family: Courier; color: rgb(194, 165, 97);">I slammed myself into the wall so many times, but I just couldn't noclip. It was like if the level was extremely stable. So, I gave up after a while—who wouldn't?—and went deeper into the level. Again and again, I was met with so many varying spaces. The funny thing is, I hadn't even realized that the level was devoid of life! I saw no entities. I saw no humans. Nothing. Nada.</span>

<span style="font-family: Courier; color: rgb(194, 165, 97);">And... I thought I was a goner. Forced to spend my life here for, oh I don't know, all of eternity. I started to go insane. I ran. I ran, ran, and ran as fast as I could. But, obviously, there was no exit. I honestly thought there was no exit at all until...</span>

<span style="font-family: Courier; color: rgb(194, 165, 97);">The distortion.</span>

<span style="font-family: Courier; color: rgb(194, 165, 97);">Here, my memory fails, so if you're still listening, ha ha. Anyways, so after about a bajillion years of wandering, I noticed my vision was getting weird. At first I thought: "Great, I'm fucked. My sanity's dropping, and I don't got Almond Water." But I noticed the walls began fading into different colors. The floors, the ceiling, all of it.</span>

<span style="font-family: Courier; color: rgb(194, 165, 97);">It was beautiful in a way. The merging of the colors, the iridescent—I think that was the word—walls resembling Dullness walls in a game. I wish I had a camera, but of course I didn't. Oh no, who'll believe me now?</span>

<span style="font-family: Courier; color: rgb(194, 165, 97);">''*chuckles*''</span>

<span style="font-family: Courier; color: rgb(194, 165, 97);">The walls fragmented. The floor cracked. The ceiling shifted. Me? I was half dead from fright. I could feel the space around be critically distorting beyond comprehension. I could hear and feel it, too. It felt like if time was stopped all around me. It sounded like if reality could contort—cold, harsh, and an amalgamation of indiscernible noises. And before I knew it, the space around me had warped into an endless darkness. Soon after, I realized where I was.</span>

<span style="font-family: Courier; color: rgb(194, 165, 97);">It was... the boundless expanse of the Void.</span>

<span style="font-family: Courier; color: rgb(194, 165, 97);">I fell... fell... fell...</span>

<span style="font-family: Courier; color: rgb(194, 165, 97);">Fell farther away from consciousness...</span>

<span style="font-family: Courier; color: rgb(194, 165, 97);">It was here that I sorta gave up. Just flat out quit on life.</span>

<span style="font-family: Courier; color: rgb(194, 165, 97);">About a dozen seconds passed by before I was assaulted with a bright yellow light and the deafening noise of fluorescent lights. I shielded my eyes from the sight before I landed with a hard ''thump'' on moist carpet.</span>

<span style="font-family: Courier; color: rgb(194, 165, 97);">I'm sure you can guess where I found myself.</span>

<span style="font-family: Courier; color: rgb(194, 165, 97);">''*sigh*''</span>

<span style="font-family: Courier; color: rgb(194, 165, 97);">I'll never forget the world I traversed. For the most part, it was truly a dull infinity. A word for travelers, ''never come here''.</span>

<span style="font-family: Courier; color: rgb(194, 165, 97);">That's... bout it. I'll be turning in this log to the M.E.G. See ya...</span>

